# =============================================================================
# Trivy ignore list — pravara-mes
# =============================================================================
#
# Format: one rule ID (or CVE) per line. Lines starting with '#' are comments.
# Trivy automatically reads .trivyignore from the scan working directory.
#
# Each entry below MUST include a rationale and a re-evaluation cue (date,
# upstream link, or condition). When the condition is met, remove the entry
# and let the scanner re-flag if the issue still exists.
#
# References:
#   - Trivy CLI: https://trivy.dev/latest/docs/configuration/filtering/
#   - aquasecurity/trivy-action reads .trivyignore by default since v0.18.0
#
# =============================================================================
# K8s misconfiguration false positives
# =============================================================================

# KSV-0039 — "containers should not run with a low UID" / namespace LimitRange missing
# KSV-0040 — "containers should not run with a low GID"  / namespace ResourceQuota missing
#
# Trivy emits these once per scanned manifest file (~57 + ~56 alerts in pravara-mes)
# even though the namespace-level policies are declared in
#   infra/k8s/base/namespace.yaml
# at lines 17-29 (ResourceQuota: pravara-quota) and 31-44 (LimitRange:
# pravara-limits). Trivy's filesystem scan mode treats each YAML file as an
# isolated package and does not follow the LimitRange chain.
#
# Verification:
#   $ trivy config infra/k8s/base/    # scans whole dir, alerts persist
#   $ kubectl -n pravara-mes get limitrange,resourcequota
#     # -> pravara-quota + pravara-limits should be Active
#
# Re-evaluation cue: when Trivy gains cross-file context for namespace policies
# (tracked at https://github.com/aquasecurity/trivy/issues), or when this
# repo migrates to a single-bundle scan workflow, remove these two lines.
KSV-0039
KSV-0040
